"""AP Capstone: 2 units — AP Seminar and AP Research"""

def P(q,ex,a,diff): return {"q":q,"ex":ex,"a":a,"diff":diff}
def T(title,problems): return {"title":title,"problems":problems}

AP_CAP = [
  # Unit 1 — AP Seminar
  [
    T("Questioning and Exploring",[
      P("What is the QUEST framework in AP Seminar?","Think systematic inquiry process.","QUEST framework guides research: Question and Explore (identify a research question and explore its complexity); Understand and Analyze (deeply understand sources and analyze arguments); Evaluate Multiple Perspectives (consider diverse viewpoints); Synthesize Ideas (bring sources together to build an original argument); Team, Transform, and Transmit (collaborate and communicate findings). AP Seminar develops these skills as transferable academic practices — not content-specific but process-specific. The framework recognizes that complex, real-world problems require questioning assumptions, analyzing multiple sources, and synthesizing diverse perspectives rather than finding a single 'right answer.'","medium"),
      P("How do you identify a strong research question?","Think scope, debatability, and significance.","Strong research question: (1) Arguable — not answerable with yes/no or simple fact lookup; (2) Appropriately scoped — not so broad that nothing can be said; not so narrow that it's trivial; (3) Significant — matters beyond academic exercise; connects to real-world problems; (4) Researchable — sufficient credible sources available; (5) Original — not just summarizing existing knowledge but contributing something. Test: can you imagine people reasonably disagreeing about the answer? Can you find multiple credible perspectives? Does answering it matter? Weak questions: 'What is climate change?' Strong: 'What policy approaches most effectively balance economic development with climate mitigation in low-income countries?'","medium"),
      P("What does it mean to analyze an argument rather than summarize it?","Think claim, evidence, reasoning, and assumptions.","Argument analysis goes beyond 'author says X.' Full analysis examines: (1) Claim: what is the author arguing? (2) Evidence: what support is provided — is it sufficient, relevant, credible? (3) Reasoning: how does the author move from evidence to claim — is the logic valid? (4) Assumptions: what must be true for the argument to work — are these stated or hidden? (5) Perspective/context: what position does the author write from — how might that shape their argument? (6) Limitations: what does the argument not address? What counterevidence exists? Asking 'so what?' and 'why?' about each element moves analysis beyond summary.","hard"),
      P("How do you evaluate source credibility?","Think SIFT and lateral reading.","Source evaluation strategies: SIFT — Stop (don't automatically believe or share), Investigate the source (who is this? what are their credentials, affiliations, potential biases?), Find better coverage (is this confirmed elsewhere?), Trace claims to original context (often quoted out of context). Lateral reading: rather than reading deeply into one source, search what others say about that source — fact-checkers, academic responses. Credibility factors: author credentials and affiliations; publication peer-review status; funding sources; date of publication; methodology transparency (for research); whether claims are sourced. Wikipedia: useful starting point for orientation but not citable — use its references.","medium"),
      P("What is perspective-taking in AP Seminar?","Think beyond your own viewpoint.","Perspective-taking: systematically considering how different stakeholders understand a problem — not just listing 'perspectives' but genuinely understanding why reasonable people hold different views. Process: (1) Identify affected parties and relevant experts; (2) Understand their values, interests, and evidence; (3) Find where perspectives agree and disagree; (4) Ask: what would someone have to believe for their position to be reasonable? (5) Avoid straw man — represent each view at its strongest. Why it matters: most real-world problems involve genuine value conflicts, not just ignorance. A policy that seems obviously correct from one vantage point may have serious costs from another. Understanding multiple perspectives is prerequisite to effective argument and collaboration.","medium"),
      P("How do you synthesize multiple sources into an argument?","Think your thesis as the organizing principle.","Synthesis: using multiple sources to build an original argument — not reporting what each says sequentially but weaving them together to support your position. Process: (1) Establish your thesis first — what are you arguing? (2) Select sources that contribute to that argument (some supporting, some complicating, some contrasting); (3) Group sources by what they contribute to different aspects of your argument; (4) Use sources as evidence within your paragraphs, not as paragraphs themselves; (5) Explicitly connect sources to each other (Source A's claim is supported by Source B; however, Source C complicates this by...); (6) Your voice frames, interprets, and concludes — sources serve your argument. Synthesis ≠ citation collection.","hard"),
      P("What is the AP Seminar Individual Research Report?","Think IWA and process requirements.","AP Seminar Individual Written Argument (IWA): 2,000-word scholarly argument addressing the AP Seminar prompt; uses 5+ credible sources; must demonstrate: inquiry (developing and refining a research question), argument (clear thesis with evidence and reasoning), perspective-taking (addressing multiple perspectives), and synthesis (original argument drawing on sources). Scored by AP teacher and by College Board AP reader. Also: Individual Oral Presentation (8 minutes) presenting and defending the IWA. Team Project: collaborative research presentation and paper on a complex issue. The whole course builds these research and argumentation skills.","medium"),
      P("What distinguishes a claim from an observation or a fact?","Think argument vs. description.","Fact/observation: verifiable, not debatable — 'The US spends more on healthcare per capita than any other developed nation.' Claim/argument: interpretation or recommendation that requires reasoning and evidence — 'The US healthcare spending is inefficient because it does not produce proportionally better outcomes.' Claims can be: (1) Claims of fact (debatable factual assertions: 'Social media causes teen depression'); (2) Claims of value (evaluations: 'Universal healthcare is more just than a market-based system'); (3) Claims of policy (recommendations: 'The US should implement Medicare for All'). AP Seminar requires making and defending claims — not just reporting facts or expressing preferences without reasoning.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Understanding and Analyzing",[
      P("What is academic integrity and how does it apply to AP Seminar?","Think citation and original contribution.","Academic integrity in AP Seminar: (1) Cite all sources — direct quotation in quotation marks with attribution; paraphrase with attribution; even ideas need credit; (2) No plagiarism — submitting others' work as your own, whether copied or AI-generated; (3) No fabrication — inventing sources or data; (4) Collaboration boundaries — Team Project is collaborative; IWA is individual; (5) AI policy: generated text must be disclosed; AI as research tool vs. AI writing your argument. Why it matters: academic community depends on trust; plagiarism misrepresents your capabilities; citation credits intellectual debts. AP Capstone portfolio is reviewed by College Board — integrity violations have serious consequences.","easy"),
      P("How do you construct an effective thesis for a complex research argument?","Think complexity and roadmap.","Complex research thesis: goes beyond simple assertion to acknowledge complexity. Components: (1) Your central claim (what you argue); (2) The 'so what' (why this matters); (3) Often a concession (acknowledging the counter-position) before asserting your claim (Although X, I argue Y because Z). Example of complex thesis: 'Although social media platforms argue that their algorithms simply reflect user preferences, the evidence demonstrates that algorithmic amplification of outrage actively undermines democratic deliberation — necessitating regulatory intervention that balances free expression with platform accountability.' This is arguable, specific, acknowledges complexity, and signals the argument's direction.","hard"),
      P("What is the difference between evidence and reasoning?","Think support vs. connection.","Evidence: the factual support for a claim — statistics, research findings, expert testimony, case studies, examples. Reasoning: the explanation of HOW and WHY the evidence supports the claim — the logical connection between evidence and conclusion. Without evidence: assertion without support. Without reasoning: data dump without interpretation. Both are required: present evidence → explain what it shows → explain why this supports your claim. Common error: presenting a quote or statistic as if it speaks for itself — it doesn't. Your reasoning shows you understand what the evidence means and why it's relevant. Reasoning also includes addressing assumptions: why is this evidence reliable? What are its limitations?","medium"),
      P("How do you address counterarguments effectively?","Think concede-and-refute.","Counterargument strategy: (1) Identify the strongest version of the opposing view — don't attack straw men; (2) Concede what's valid: 'It is true that...'; (3) Explain the limitation: 'However, this fails to account for...'; (4) Return to your claim strengthened. Why this matters: demonstrates intellectual honesty; prevents readers from dismissing your argument because you ignored obvious objections; shows your position can withstand scrutiny. Types of counterarguments: alternative explanations for your evidence; evidence that contradicts yours; values-based objections to your conclusion; practical objections to your policy recommendations. Engaging rather than ignoring the opposition makes your argument stronger.","medium"),
      P("What rhetorical strategies are effective in academic argument?","Think appeals and structure.","Academic rhetoric: (1) Ethos — establish credibility through accurate citation, careful reasoning, acknowledgment of complexity, scholarly tone; (2) Logos — logical structure, evidence, valid reasoning, clear thesis, organized argument; (3) Pathos — appropriate and limited; real-world stakes and human consequences give significance without emotional manipulation. Structural strategies: organize paragraphs by claim (not by source); use topic sentences that advance the argument; use transitions that show logical relationships (therefore, however, consequently, although); vary sentence structure for clarity and emphasis. AP Seminar academic register: formal vocabulary, third person generally, hedging language for uncertain claims (suggests, indicates, may, arguably).","medium"),
      P("What is the difference between primary and secondary sources?","Think original vs. interpretation.","Primary sources: original, firsthand materials — raw data, original research studies, historical documents, speeches, interviews, literary texts, works of art, laws, treaties. Examples: a scientific study, census data, The Federalist Papers, an autobiography, a photograph. Secondary sources: interpret, analyze, or comment on primary sources — articles about a study, historical analyses, literary criticism, textbooks, documentary films. Examples: a review article summarizing research, a history textbook, a critique of a novel. Using both: primary sources provide the 'what'; secondary sources provide analytical frameworks and scholarly interpretations. AP Seminar should engage with primary evidence AND scholarly secondary analysis — not just secondary summaries.","easy"),
      P("How do you present complex research findings in an oral presentation?","Think clarity and engagement.","Oral presentation strategies: (1) Know your audience — AP exam evaluators want to see your reasoning, not just your conclusions; (2) Structure: brief attention-getter, research question, key findings/argument, evidence, significance; (3) Simplify without dumbing down — distill complex argument to its essence; (4) Visual support — slides should illuminate, not read your script; (5) Eye contact and engagement — don't read your notes; (6) Anticipate questions — what will the evaluator ask? Prepare for defense; (7) Time management — 8 minutes is short; practice aloud; (8) Authentic voice — academic but natural. Common errors: reading verbatim; too much content; too little argument; visual clutter.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Evaluating and Synthesizing",[
      P("What makes a source academically credible for AP Seminar?","Think peer review, expertise, transparency.","Credibility criteria: (1) Peer-reviewed academic journals: expert review before publication; gold standard for empirical claims; found via Google Scholar, JSTOR, PubMed; (2) Expert authors: relevant credentials (PhD in relevant field, institutional affiliation); (3) Reputable publishers: university presses, established news organizations with editorial standards; (4) Transparent methodology: research studies explain how data was collected and analyzed; (5) Recent (for empirical questions): science advances; older studies may be outdated; (6) Cited by others: if a source is frequently cited in the field, it's considered credible. Less credible: Wikipedia, anonymous sources, advocacy websites without evidence, news from partisan sources without corroboration, social media posts.","medium"),
      P("How do you balance breadth and depth in a research argument?","Think scope and specificity.","Breadth vs. depth tension: Breadth: covering many aspects of a topic, multiple perspectives, range of sources. Depth: deep analysis of specific evidence, thoroughly reasoned claims, close engagement with complexity. AP Seminar resolution: depth over breadth for the IWA. A 2,000-word paper cannot thoroughly examine ten aspects — focus on 2-3 key claims examined deeply. Strategy: identify your central research question → select 2-3 most important sub-questions → for each, find the strongest evidence and reason through it carefully. Breadth shows up in perspective-taking (acknowledging other views) — not in trying to cover everything. A deep, well-reasoned argument on a focused question outperforms a shallow survey of many points.","hard"),
      P("What is interdisciplinary thinking and why does AP Seminar value it?","Think connections across fields.","Interdisciplinary thinking: bringing concepts, methods, and evidence from multiple disciplines to address a complex question. Why: most important real-world problems (climate change, poverty, public health, AI ethics) cannot be fully addressed by one discipline — economics alone misses cultural factors; biology alone misses policy dimensions. How: (1) Identify what each relevant discipline contributes to understanding your question; (2) Find where disciplines agree and disagree; (3) Explain how insights from multiple fields create a fuller picture than any single field. Example: researching algorithmic bias requires computer science (how algorithms work), sociology (structural inequalities), law (civil rights framework), ethics (values questions). AP Seminar intentionally spans disciplines.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Team Collaboration",[
      P("How does the AP Seminar Team Project work?","Think collaborative research and presentation.","Team Project (TMP): groups of 3-5 students collaborate on a research project around the AP Seminar course theme. Components: (1) Team Multimedia Presentation (TMP): 8-10 minutes + defense; all members contribute; evaluators observe; each member's individual contribution assessed; (2) Individual Written Argument (IWA): each member writes their own 2,000-word paper on a narrower aspect of the team topic. Process: negotiate roles and contributions; divide research areas; synthesize team findings; present coherently. Challenges: equitable contribution; managing disagreement; synthesizing diverse individual research. AP scoring: individual scores based on observable individual contribution — everyone's role must be visible.","medium"),
      P("What communication skills are essential in collaborative research?","Think academic teamwork.","Collaborative research skills: (1) Active listening — understanding teammates' ideas before responding; (2) Constructive disagreement — challenge ideas, not people; 'I see it differently because...' not 'You're wrong'; (3) Building on others' ideas — 'Yes, and...' rather than dismissing; (4) Negotiating scope — agreeing on research question boundaries; (5) Dividing work equitably — clear ownership of sections; (6) Synthesizing across contributions — connecting individual research into coherent argument; (7) Peer feedback — giving and receiving specific, actionable critique; (8) Documentation — keeping records of decisions and contributions. Real-world connection: nearly all professional work is collaborative; AP Seminar develops these skills intentionally.","medium"),
      P("How do you manage and resolve disagreement in a research team?","Think productive conflict.","Managing team disagreement: (1) Distinguish content disagreement (about the argument) from process disagreement (about how to work) — different solutions; (2) Make disagreements explicit — unclear tension undermines collaboration; (3) Use evidence as arbiter — 'what does the research show?' grounds debate; (4) Consider multiple framings — often both positions capture something true; (5) Document the disagreement and resolution; (6) Seek mediation from instructor if irresolvable; (7) Acknowledge in your argument when evidence points in different directions — intellectual honesty. Content disagreements can actually strengthen the final product by surfacing genuine complexity. The goal is not comfortable agreement but the best possible argument.","medium"),
      P("What is the AP Seminar end-of-course exam?","Think source-based analysis.","AP Seminar Exam: Part A (individual written argument, 4 hours): analyze a set of sources provided to you on exam day around the course theme; write an evidence-based argument; no outside sources allowed; demonstrate synthesis, analysis, and argumentation. Part B (team multimedia presentation): occurs during the school year, not exam day. Scoring: IWA (45%), TMP (45%), End-of-Course Exam (10%). The exam tests the same skills practiced all year — analyzing sources, identifying arguments and evidence, evaluating perspectives, synthesizing into original argument — but applied to unfamiliar sources. Preparation: practice reading complex texts quickly; practice building arguments from provided sources; develop thesis quickly from multiple sources.","easy"),
    ]),
    T("Argument and Research Writing",[
      P("What is the MEAL paragraph structure for academic writing?","Think claim, evidence, analysis, link.","MEAL paragraph structure: Main idea (topic sentence — the claim this paragraph makes); Evidence (specific support from sources — quotation, paraphrase, data); Analysis (your interpretation — what does this evidence show? how does it support the claim?); Link (connection to thesis or next paragraph). Why MEAL: ensures every paragraph has a clear purpose, sufficient evidence, and genuine analysis. Common errors: paragraphs that are only evidence (no analysis); paragraphs with multiple claims (no focus); paragraphs with analysis but no evidence (assertion); paragraphs that don't link to thesis. MEAL is not rigid formula — varies by context — but provides scaffold for developing academic writing habits.","medium"),
      P("How do you write an effective introduction for an academic research argument?","Think hook, context, and thesis.","Academic introduction structure: (1) Opening — engage with the problem's significance (not 'Since the dawn of time...'): a striking statistic, an illustrative case, a provocative question; (2) Context — briefly establish necessary background so reader understands the problem; (3) Identify the gap or problem — why is this question open? what's at stake?; (4) Thesis — your specific, arguable claim about the question. Length: introductions are typically short relative to body — 10-15% of total paper. Avoid: throat-clearing ('This paper will discuss...'); overly broad openings; thesis buried at the end of a long vague introduction; making claims the paper won't support. The introduction creates a 'contract' with the reader — promise only what you'll deliver.","medium"),
      P("How do you cite sources correctly in AP Seminar?","Think MLA format and in-text citation.","AP Seminar uses MLA format: In-text citation: (Author Page) at end of sentence before period — (Smith 42); or (Author) if page not applicable for websites. Quote integration: signal phrase + quote + citation: According to Smith, 'direct quote here' (42). Works Cited page: alphabetical by author last name; standard format for each source type (book: Last, First. Title. Publisher, Year; journal article: Last, First. 'Article Title.' Journal Name, vol., no., year, pp. DOI/URL). Paraphrase citation: rephrase in your own words + citation — still requires attribution. No citation = plagiarism even if paraphrased. Why it matters: allows reader to verify and investigate your sources; credits intellectual debts; demonstrates engagement with scholarly community.","easy"),
      P("What distinguishes an excellent AP Seminar paper from a good one?","Think sophistication and integration.","Excellence criteria: (1) Sophisticated thesis — not a simple for/against but captures genuine complexity ('Although..., the evidence suggests that... because..., which means...'); (2) Best evidence — not just any source but the most credible, specific, and relevant evidence available; (3) Developed analysis — not 'this shows X' but 'this demonstrates X because..., which is significant because...'; (4) Genuine perspective-taking — not tokenistic 'some say' but actual engagement with why reasonable people disagree; (5) Seamless synthesis — sources in conversation with each other, not reported sequentially; (6) Strong voice — the paper sounds like a human thinker, not a source collection; (7) Significant 'so what' — conclusion that explains why this matters beyond the paper.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Research Methods",[
      P("What is the difference between quantitative and qualitative research?","Think numbers vs. meaning.","Quantitative research: measures phenomena numerically; tests hypotheses; uses statistics; seeks generalizable findings; randomized controlled trials, surveys with large samples, longitudinal studies. Strengths: can establish causation (experiment), reveal patterns across large populations, test predictions precisely. Qualitative research: explores meaning, experience, and context; uses words not numbers; interviews, ethnography, case studies, discourse analysis. Strengths: captures complexity and nuance; explores phenomena where measurement is inappropriate; generates hypotheses; explains the 'why' behind quantitative patterns. Mixed methods: combines both — use qualitative to understand why quantitative patterns occur. AP Seminar: both types of sources are valuable; understanding what each can and cannot answer is key to evaluating evidence.","medium"),
      P("What are common logical fallacies to avoid in research arguments?","Think flawed reasoning patterns.","Logical fallacies: (1) Ad hominem: attacking the person not the argument; (2) Straw man: misrepresenting the opposing view; (3) False dichotomy: only presenting two options when more exist; (4) Slippery slope: claiming one step inevitably leads to extreme outcome without showing why; (5) Appeal to authority: citing authority without relevant expertise; (6) Hasty generalization: drawing broad conclusion from insufficient evidence; (7) Correlation-causation confusion: two things correlate doesn't mean one causes the other; (8) Anecdotal evidence: one example doesn't establish a pattern; (9) Appeal to popularity: many people believe it therefore it's true; (10) Confirmation bias: only citing sources that support your view. Identifying fallacies both in your own argument and in sources you evaluate.","hard"),
      P("How does sampling affect the validity of research findings?","Think who the study actually tells us about.","Sampling: how research participants are selected determines to whom findings apply (external validity). Random sample: every member of population has equal chance of selection → results can be generalized to population. Convenience sample: whoever is available (common in psychology using college students) → limited generalizability. Self-selection bias: people who volunteer for studies may differ systematically from those who don't. Sample size: larger samples more reliable; small samples produce unstable estimates. Demographic representation: if sample is all white, male, or Western, findings may not apply to other groups. WEIRD bias: Western, Educated, Industrialized, Rich, Democratic — most psychological research uses WEIRD samples; may not apply globally. Evaluating research requires asking: who was studied? Can we generalize?","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Presentation and Defense",[
      P("How do you defend your research argument in a Q&A?","Think anticipating and responding to challenges.","Research defense strategies: (1) Anticipate objections: before presenting, list the three strongest counterarguments — prepare responses; (2) Listen carefully to questions: understand exactly what is being challenged before responding; (3) Acknowledge valid points: 'That's a fair challenge; I'd respond by...' — shows intellectual honesty; (4) Distinguish between a question challenging your evidence vs. your reasoning vs. your values — different responses; (5) Know your sources: be able to explain what each source actually says and why it's credible; (6) Be comfortable with uncertainty: 'My research doesn't fully resolve that question, but suggests...' is honest and appropriate; (7) Don't get defensive: challenge is an opportunity to deepen the argument, not a personal attack.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("AP Seminar Exam Preparation",[
      P("What strategies help succeed on the AP Seminar end-of-course exam?","Think source analysis under time pressure.","Exam strategies: (1) Read the prompt and stimulus materials in order: overview → prompt → sources; understand what you're arguing about before diving into sources; (2) Annotate sources quickly: mark key claims, evidence, perspectives, limitations; (3) Draft thesis before writing: 5-10 minutes planning saves more time than it takes; (4) Manage time: 4 hours total; leave 30 minutes for revision; (5) Quote sources but analyze: don't let sources do the arguing for you; (6) Address all perspectives: show you understand multiple sides even if advocating one; (7) Write clearly and directly: exam readers assess argumentation, not vocabulary display; (8) Strong conclusion: 'so what' — what are the implications of your argument? (9) Proofread: check thesis against body; check citations; fix obvious errors.","medium"),
    ]),
  ],
  # Unit 2 — AP Research
  [
    T("Designing a Research Study",[
      P("What is the AP Research Academic Paper and what does it require?","Think independent research project.","AP Research Academic Paper: 4,000–5,000 word scholarly paper presenting original research; culminating product of the AP Research course. Requirements: (1) Research question (compelling, significant, researchable); (2) Literature review (situate your question in existing scholarship); (3) Research methodology (explains how you gathered and analyzed data or how you analyzed existing texts); (4) Findings/results (what you discovered); (5) Discussion/conclusion (what your findings mean; limitations; implications for further research). Also: 20-minute oral defense before a panel. Scored by AP teacher and College Board. Builds on AP Seminar skills but adds original data collection (primary research) or original analysis of existing texts/data.","medium"),
      P("How do you develop a research question for AP Research?","Think originality and feasibility.","AP Research question development: must be narrower and more feasible than AP Seminar. Requirements: (1) Gap in existing literature — what question hasn't been fully answered?; (2) Researchable with available methods and resources (high school student, 8 months, no lab access?); (3) Ethical — no research that harms participants; (4) Original contribution — not just replicating existing research; (5) Significant — why does the answer matter? Refinement process: start broad → read existing research → find gaps and unanswered questions → narrow to specific, feasible question. Common mistake: question too broad (impossible to answer) or too narrow (trivial). Examples: community study of local issue; textual analysis of overlooked literary texts; secondary analysis of existing datasets; survey study of accessible population.","hard"),
      P("What is a literature review and how do you write one?","Think situating your question in existing scholarship.","Literature review: critical synthesis of existing research related to your question — not a summary of each article but an organized argument about what is known and what remains unknown. Structure: (1) Introduce the topic and its significance; (2) Organize thematically (not chronologically or source-by-source) — group sources by what they contribute; (3) Identify agreements and disagreements in the literature; (4) Identify gaps — what hasn't been answered? (5) Explain how your research addresses the gap. Why: demonstrates you know the field; prevents reinventing the wheel; situates your contribution; shows reviewers you can critically evaluate scholarship. Length: typically 20-30% of total paper. Citation: every claim about existing research must be cited.","hard"),
      P("How do you select the appropriate research methodology?","Think matching method to question.","Methodology selection: the method must match the research question. Qualitative: questions about meaning, experience, culture, interpretation — interviews, focus groups, ethnography, discourse analysis, close reading of texts. Quantitative: questions about frequency, relationships, causes — surveys with statistical analysis, secondary data analysis, natural experiments. Mixed methods: combining both — qualitative to understand context, quantitative to measure scope. Historical/archival: questions about past events — primary source analysis, oral history. Computational: analyzing large datasets, text mining, network analysis. Considerations: What can I realistically access? What will answer my specific question? What are ethical constraints? Does my method match standards in the relevant discipline? Justify your methodology choice in your paper.","hard"),
      P("What are the ethical requirements for research involving human participants?","Think IRB and informed consent.","Human subjects protection: Institutional Review Board (IRB) reviews research involving human participants to protect from harm. High school research: seek teacher/school approval equivalent to IRB review. Principles: (1) Informed consent — participants must be told what they're participating in and agree voluntarily; (2) Confidentiality — protect identity; anonymize data; (3) Minimal risk — benefits must outweigh risks; avoid psychological harm; (4) Right to withdraw — participants can leave at any time without penalty; (5) Special protections for vulnerable populations (minors, incarcerated, cognitively impaired). AP Research: any study with human participants requires ethical approval process; must be documented in methodology section. Most AP Research projects can be designed to minimize ethical complications.","medium"),
      P("What is the difference between validity and reliability in research?","Think accuracy vs. consistency.","Validity: does the measure actually measure what it claims to measure? Internal validity: does the study actually demonstrate the relationship claimed (not just correlation)? External validity: can findings be generalized beyond the specific study? Construct validity: does the measure capture the theoretical concept? Reliability: does the measure produce consistent results if repeated? A reliable measure gives the same result each time; but a reliable measure can be consistently wrong (valid but not reliable = scattered; reliable but not valid = consistently hitting the wrong target). Both required for good research. Threats: sampling bias undermines external validity; confounding variables undermine internal validity; poorly designed survey instruments undermine construct validity.","hard"),
      P("How do you analyze qualitative data?","Think coding and thematic analysis.","Qualitative data analysis: (1) Transcribe interviews or fieldnotes accurately; (2) Read through all data for overall impression; (3) Open coding — identify and label meaningful segments; (4) Axial coding — group related codes into categories; (5) Selective coding — identify core themes that emerge across data; (6) Thematic analysis — describe each theme with supporting evidence (quotes); (7) Consider negative cases — examples that don't fit the pattern; (8) Reflexivity — acknowledge how your own position shapes interpretation. Software: NVivo, Atlas.ti for larger projects; manual coding fine for smaller. Rigor: member checking (show participants your interpretation), triangulation (multiple data sources), thick description (rich contextual detail), negative case analysis.","hard"),
      P("How do you present findings from original research?","Think reporting vs. interpreting.","Presenting findings: Reporting (Results section): what did you find? — present data, themes, patterns without yet interpreting them. For quantitative: tables, charts, statistics. For qualitative: themes with supporting quotes. For textual analysis: organized presentation of textual evidence. Interpreting (Discussion section): what do findings mean? — connect to your research question; explain what findings suggest; compare to existing literature (how do your findings agree, disagree, or extend prior work?); address alternative explanations; acknowledge limitations; suggest implications for further research. Distinction matters: first show the reader the evidence; then interpret it. Common error: mixing results and interpretation, or discussing without showing the evidence first.","medium"),
    ]),
    T("Literature Review and Scholarly Context",[
      P("How do you critically evaluate existing research for your literature review?","Think beyond accepting what published sources say.","Critical evaluation of literature: even peer-reviewed research has limitations. Questions to ask: (1) Sample — who was studied? Can findings generalize? (2) Methodology — does the method actually answer the research question? (3) Confounding variables — what else might explain the results? (4) Effect size — is a statistically significant effect also practically significant? (5) Replication — has this been replicated? Single studies are preliminary; consistent findings across multiple studies are more reliable; (6) Conflict of interest — who funded the study? Does industry funding correlate with industry-favorable results? (7) Year — is more recent research available? In fast-moving fields, 5-year-old research may be outdated. Critical evaluation demonstrates scholarly sophistication.","hard"),
      P("What is the IMRAD structure and when is it used?","Think scientific paper format.","IMRAD: Introduction, Methods, Results, And Discussion — standard structure for empirical research papers (scientific and social science). Introduction: research question, background, significance, hypothesis. Methods: participants, materials, procedure, analysis — enough detail to replicate. Results: findings only — no interpretation. Discussion: interpretation, comparison to existing literature, limitations, implications, conclusion. When used: experimental studies, surveys, observational research. Not used: humanities papers, theoretical analyses, literature reviews (which have different structures). AP Research: if doing empirical research (surveys, experiments), IMRAD appropriate; if doing textual analysis or historical research, adapt structure to disciplinary conventions of relevant field.","medium"),
      P("How do you synthesize conflicting findings in a literature review?","Think productive tension.","Conflicting findings in literature: (1) Identify the conflict precisely — do studies use different definitions? different populations? different methods? (2) Explain why they might conflict (methodological differences, context differences, time period differences); (3) Identify which findings are more credible and why (larger sample? better controls? more recent? replicated?); (4) If genuinely unresolved: acknowledge the debate and explain what your research contributes to resolving it. Don't: ignore conflicting evidence; pretend consensus where none exists; arbitrarily pick the side that supports your hypothesis. Conflicting literature often reveals a gap that your research can address — a reason your original research is needed.","hard"),
      P("What is academic discourse and how do you enter it?","Think joining a scholarly conversation.","Academic discourse: the ongoing conversation among scholars in a field — carried out through publications, conference presentations, and peer review. Entering it: (1) Know the existing conversation — literature review shows you've read what's been said; (2) Identify your position — where do you agree, disagree, extend, complicate existing work?; (3) Speak the language — use disciplinary terminology correctly; (4) Cite predecessors — academic convention requires acknowledging intellectual debts; (5) Submit to review — the peer review process is how scholars test arguments. AP Research paper: a simulation of academic discourse — you're practicing the form and norms of scholarly contribution. The best AP Research papers read like genuine scholarly contributions to their field.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Methodology and Data",[
      P("What is triangulation and why does it strengthen research?","Think multiple evidence sources.","Triangulation: using multiple methods, data sources, or investigators to examine a research question — convergence of evidence from different angles increases confidence in findings. Types: (1) Data triangulation — same question studied at different times, places, or with different participants; (2) Method triangulation — combining qualitative and quantitative approaches; (3) Investigator triangulation — multiple researchers analyze same data (checks individual bias); (4) Theory triangulation — analyzing data from multiple theoretical frameworks. Why: any single method has limitations; when multiple independent methods converge on the same finding, confidence increases; when they diverge, it reveals complexity worth examining. Particularly important in qualitative research where researcher subjectivity is a concern.","hard"),
      P("How do you interpret quantitative data from surveys?","Think descriptive and inferential statistics.","Survey data analysis: (1) Descriptive statistics: describe the sample — mean, median, mode (central tendency); range, standard deviation (spread); frequency distributions; percentages. Present in tables and charts; (2) Inferential statistics: make inferences about the population — t-tests (compare two groups), ANOVA (compare multiple groups), chi-square (relationships between categorical variables), correlation (relationship between continuous variables), regression (predict one variable from another); (3) Statistical significance (p-value): probability that result occurred by chance; p<0.05 means less than 5% chance of chance finding; (4) Effect size: how large is the effect in practical terms? — matters as much as significance; (5) Limitations: survey response bias, sampling, self-report accuracy.","hard"),
      P("What are the characteristics of a strong research methodology section?","Think reproducibility and justification.","Strong methodology section: (1) Complete — enough detail that another researcher could replicate the study; (2) Justified — explains WHY each methodological choice was made (not just what); (3) Ethical — explains how participant rights were protected; (4) Addressed validity and reliability — explains how threats were minimized; (5) Clear sequence — participants, instruments/materials, procedure, analysis — in logical order; (6) Limitations acknowledged — what does this method not capture? (7) Pilot testing noted if conducted — preliminary testing of instruments or procedures. Reproducibility: the foundation of science is that others can check your work; if your methodology is unclear or insufficient, findings cannot be evaluated or built upon.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("Writing and Defending Research",[
      P("How do you write a strong discussion section?","Think interpreting your own findings.","Discussion section structure: (1) Restate your main findings in relation to your research question (without raw data — that's in Results); (2) Interpret findings — what do they mean? what do they tell us?; (3) Compare to literature — how do your findings align with or diverge from prior research? explain convergence and divergence; (4) Address alternative explanations — what else could explain your findings?; (5) Limitations — what are the weaknesses of your study? (sample, method, scope, time); (6) Implications — so what? what does this mean for theory, practice, or policy?; (7) Future research — what questions does your research raise that remain unanswered? Avoid: overstating conclusions beyond what data support; ignoring unexpected findings; repeating Results rather than interpreting them.","hard"),
      P("How do you prepare for the AP Research oral defense?","Think explaining and defending your choices.","Oral defense preparation: (1) Know every choice you made and WHY — evaluators ask about methodology, source selection, analysis decisions; (2) Know your literature review — what are the key sources and what do they say?; (3) Know your findings in depth — not just what you found but patterns, outliers, and nuance; (4) Anticipate methodological critiques: 'How do you know this wasn't caused by X?' 'How representative is your sample?'; (5) Practice explaining complex ideas simply; (6) Be honest about limitations — you know them better than evaluators do; (7) Know what your research contributes — why does this matter?; (8) 20 minutes total; typically 8-10 minute overview + 10-12 minute Q&A. The defense tests depth of understanding, not memorized content.","medium"),
      P("What makes an original contribution in AP Research?","Think what only your study can show.","Original contribution: what does your research add that wasn't there before? Types of original contribution: (1) New data: original survey, interviews, or observations filling a gap in existing evidence; (2) New context: applying a question previously studied in one context (urban) to another (rural); testing whether findings from one population (adults) hold for another (teenagers); (3) New method: analyzing existing data with a new analytical approach; (4) New synthesis: bringing together literatures that haven't been connected; (5) Replication: testing whether a finding holds when studied again (rare but valuable); (6) Counter-evidence: original data that challenges prevailing view. Key: your paper should make a specific, identifiable contribution that someone building on your work would cite.","hard"),
      P("How do you write an effective research conclusion?","Think significance and forward direction.","Conclusion structure: (1) Restate research question and summarize what you found (briefly — details already in Discussion); (2) State your main argument/claim — what does your research establish or suggest?; (3) Connect to broader significance — why does this matter beyond your specific study?; (4) Policy/practice implications if appropriate — what should be done differently based on your findings?; (5) Limitations (briefly if not already fully addressed in Discussion); (6) Future research directions — what questions remain? what follow-up studies are needed?; (7) Closing statement — forward-looking, not a mere restatement. Length: conclusions typically 10-15% of paper — focused and direct. Avoid: introducing new evidence; claiming more than your data support; ending with a vague platitude.","medium"),
      P("What is reflexivity in qualitative research?","Think researcher position and bias.","Reflexivity: the practice of acknowledging how the researcher's own position, identity, and assumptions shape the research process and findings. Particularly important in qualitative research where researcher is the 'instrument' of data collection and analysis. Elements: (1) Positionality statement — who are you? what experiences and assumptions do you bring?; (2) How might your background affect how you interpret what participants say?; (3) How might participants respond differently because of who you are?; (4) What theoretical frameworks shape your analysis?; (5) How did you manage potential biases (member checking, reflexive journaling, peer debriefing)?. Not an admission of failure — all research is shaped by perspective; reflexivity makes this transparent so readers can evaluate it. Quantitative research also has researcher choices that should be acknowledged.","hard"),
    ]),
    T("AP Research Portfolio",[
      P("What are all the components of the AP Research portfolio?","Think WCF, IRB, and Academic Paper.","AP Research portfolio components: (1) Academic Paper (4,000–5,000 words) — the full research paper; submitted online; scored by AP reader; (2) Presentation and Oral Defense — 20 minutes (8-10 min presentation + Q&A); scored by teacher; (3) IRB/Institutional Review Board approval documentation — ethical approval for human subjects research; required for any study involving participants; (4) Process and Reflection Portfolio — optional documentation showing development of thinking; may include: annotated bibliography, research journal, mentor communication, early drafts. Scoring: Academic Paper 75%, Presentation 25%. The academic paper alone earns 75% of the score — prioritize its quality. The paper must be submitted by April deadline regardless of presentation timing.","easy"),
      P("How does mentorship work in AP Research?","Think subject matter expert guidance.","Mentorship in AP Research: students often work with a subject matter expert outside the classroom who has expertise in the student's research area. Types: academic (professor, graduate student), professional (practitioner in the field), community (someone with relevant lived experience). Finding mentors: teacher can connect; university departments sometimes welcome high school students; LinkedIn outreach with specific, professional email; community organizations. Working with mentor: share your research question and literature review; ask specific questions about methodology; get feedback on draft; acknowledge in paper. IRB note: mentor approval may be needed for studies on sensitive topics. Not required but strongly encouraged — access to genuine expertise is a major advantage.","medium"),
    ]),
  ]
]
